               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="high" type="empire"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7024412" key="place_7024412">Ottoman
                        Empire</origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1714-09-15">on the morning of a Sunday
                        during the last days of Jumādà I 981 (either 30 Sept or 7 Oct. 1573 CE; 20
                        or 27 Sept. 1573 JD)</origDate>. </origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName>Denis-Dominique Cardonne
                           (1720–1783)</persName>, as per his inscription on folio <locus from="1a"
                           to="1a">1a</locus>. An orientalist and translator, he lived in
                        Constantinople from the age of nine for twenty years, where he served a
                        dragoman of France in the Morea (Peloponnese), before returning to France.
                        The dates of his inscription would indicate that he acquired the volume
                        shortly after his appointment as professor and Chair of Turkish and Persian
                        at the Collège royal.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>While the circumstances under which the volume arrived in Britain remain unclear, a note in the volume suggests that a Previously held in <orgName role="rps" key="person_155994771"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/155994771">Chetham's Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Purchased in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1981">1981</date> by the
                           <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                        together with other oriental manuscripts for £2000.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
